{
    "Introduction": {
        "start_index": 1312,
        "text": "**Introduction** \n\nWorkspace constrained MPC approaches, many of which incorporate kinematics model and/or perception models, are well established. Examples in literature include Asadi, et al. (2023), Bruschetta, Maran, and Beghi (2017), Bruschetta, Cenedese, and Beghi (2019), Bruschetta, et al. (2016; 2018), Fang and Kemeny (2014), Fang, Wautier, and Kemeny (2019; 2021), Garrett and Best (2013), Khusro, et al. (2020), Lamprecht, et al. (2019), Pham, Pham, and Nguyen (2023), and Qazani, et al. (2021). \n\nThese approaches are, to varying extents, difficult to tune and require expert knowledge to develop. Indeed, their adoption in industry severely lags their maturation in academia (Ghafarian, et al., 2023). \n\nClassical Washout Filter (CWF\u2019s), on the other hand, are easy to tune, easy to implement (Qazani, et al., 2024) and produce acceptable outcomes. Their simplicity makes them suited for \u201cdynamic\u201d simulator sessions where driver preferences, scenarios and car setup are changing rapidly. Keeping the simulator within workspace constraints is a challenge however. \n\nA known method for workspace limiting in CWF Motion Cueing Algorithms (CWF-MCA\u2019s) is clipping actuator motions. Consider the case of na\u00a8\u0131vely clipping position, velocity and acceleration of an actuator. Hard clipping position introduces violations (discontinuities) in velocity and acceleration. If these are clipped subsequently, the position constraint may no longer be satisfied. An advantage of hard clipping however is the clear division between \u201cnormal driving\u201d and a \u201climiting event\u201d. In the author\u2019s experience, many elite drivers prefer this over a more ambiguous combination of cueing and limiting (e.g. MPC). \n\nNonetheless, to soften discontinuities, soft clipping curves needs to be designed. This greatly complicates the parametrisation of a motion simulator. Even if implemented correctly, the effect of soft clipping a single actuator on the overall motion may introduce additional accelerations not accounted for by the vehicle model, for example, an artificial rotation caused by a single actuator reaching its limits. Moreover, the softer the clipping, the more it degrades the motion in general. Finally, any clipping may adversely interfere with recentering (washout). Additional recovery logic may therefore need to be implemented. \n\nClipping in world space (rather than actuator space) is also an option. But this is complicated by the trend for redundant degrees of freedom, for example, the popular 6 Degree of Freedom (DOF) + XY( _\u03c8_ ) configuration (Ghafarian, et al., 2023). \n\nNowadays, several simulators of different physical design may coexist in the same simulator facility (Kolff, et al., 2022). Consider MPC\u2014understanding the kinematics of each system, the possible process of its mathematical simplification, linearisation and design of a cost function is a heavy burden for commercial simulator teams. Greater productivity and transferability may be achieved if each simulator can be treated in the same way with respect to limiting. \n\nClearly, a new philosophy to workspace limiting is needed that is simple enough for day to day operation and provides a unified workflow for a large simulator centre. \n\n**Stuttgart, 24-26 Sep 2025** \n\n**-1-** \n\n**DSC 2025 Europe**<sup>VR</sup> \n\n**Meeting Workspace Constraints** \n\n### ",
        "gemini_summary": "This text explores the trade-offs between two primary motion cueing strategies for simulators: **Model Predictive Control (MPC)** and **Classical Washout Filters (CWF)**.\n\n*   **MPC Limitations:** While theoretically robust and well-documented in academia, MPC approaches are difficult to tune, require high-level expert knowledge, and suffer from poor industrial adoption. \n*   **CWF Advantages:** CWFs are favored in industrial settings for their simplicity, ease of implementation, and flexibility in fast-paced simulation environments.\n*   **The Workspace Dilemma:** The core challenge of CWFs is managing physical workspace constraints. While \"clipping\" is the standard solution, it presents significant drawbacks:\n    *   **Hard clipping** causes discontinuities that can degrade the driver experience.\n    *   **Soft clipping** introduces complex parameterization, unintended artifacts (like artificial rotations), and interference with the recentering/washout process.\n    *   **World-space clipping** is increasingly difficult to implement due to the rise of simulators with redundant degrees of freedom.\n*   **The Need for a New Approach:** Given the modern challenge of managing diverse simulator fleets, the current methodologies are inefficient. The text concludes that there is an urgent need for a unified, simplified philosophy for workspace limiting that balances the practical ease of CWFs with the effectiveness of constrained motion control."
    },
    "Separating Limiting from Kinematics": {
        "start_index": 4648,
        "text": "Separating Limiting from Kinematics \n\nKinematics vary from simulator to simulator. For a unified workspace limiter it is critical, then, that limiting occurs on e.g. driver position in an inertial (world) coordinate system\u2014convenient since washout filters typically also act in this reference frame (Brown, 2024b). This way the same limiting algorithm can be used for each simulator, albeit with different mappings (explained subsequently). \n\nIf the shape of the workspace in world coordinates is unknown then a mapping _f_ is needed from simulator states to workspace limits. For example, if the simulator is stationary and in the centred position, the driver/cockpit\u2019s acceleration limits in each of the 6 degrees of freedom may be high. If the simulator is in an offset position, acceleration limits may be reduced in that direction. This likely reflects zoning in an underlying safety-critical motion control system (Scalera, et al., 2020). \n\nLet **Xa** be simulator actuator states and **Y** + _\u2208\u211c_<sup>_n_</sup> , **Y** _\u2212 \u2208\u211c_<sup>_n_</sup> be the maximum and minimum allowed values for _n_ driver/cockpit states (position, velocity, acceleration, etc...) in all 6 degrees of freedom (surge, sway, heave, roll, pitch and yaw). Especially for overdetermined systems it is desirable to also \n\n|Simulator Control Input|\n|---|\n|Cockpit controls|\n|Vehicle Dynamics Model|\n|Vehicle states**a**|\n|Motion Cueing Algorithm (MCA)|\n|Desired driver states**\u02dca**|\n|Workspace Limiter|\n|Feasible driver states <sup>**\u00af**</sup>**\u02dca**|\n|Kinematic Transform|\n|Desired actuator states|\n|Platform Dynamics|\n|e.g. Current demands|\n|Platform Motion|\n\n\n\n**Figure 1. Modified simulator control flow chart from Telban and Cardullo (2005). The proposed workspace limiter is a separate subsystem that acts on head or h-point position,velocity, acceleration etc...** _\u2208_ **Y. This strict separation facilitates more experimentation in MCA design.** \n\nconsider the current driver/cockpit state **Y** . This information is useful for managing antagonistic demands for actuator motion from conflicting degrees of freedom (roll and heave, for example). \n\nIn summary it is desirable to _design_ : \n\n\n\nThe level of detail implemented in this mapping may vary depending on resource and budget constraints\u2014either, capturing every nuance or, providing an approximate shape to the workspace\u2014perhaps even based simply on catalogue values. \n\nThe implementation of the mapping may be mathematical, based on a kinematics model. Alternatively, it may be based on an empirically populated Look up Table (LUT)\u2014interpolation should be used as much as possible to minimise memory usage. LUT\u2019s or Piecewise Affine Functions (PWA\u2019s) are a known approach to improving computational efficiency of control algorithms, especially MPC (Chadha, et al., 2023; Fang and Kemeny, 2012; Munir, et al., 2017) \n\nIndeed, Bruschetta, et al. (2014) concluded that determining the analytical shape of a 6+3 DOF simulator workspace is too difficult in practice. A curve fitting procedure was used on a set of measurements instead. According to Bessala, Bidaud, and Ben Ouezdou (1996) \u201cexplicit direct or inverse models [of Stewart platform workspaces]... are not in general analytically possible.\u201d Some visualisations of workspaces in world coordinates are given in Grottoli, et al. (2018). \n\nThe exact method of construction of the LUT is beyond the scope of this paper\u2014is at the discretion of the practitioner. Interpolation and simplifications of the workspace should likely be used to manage its size in memory. \n\nThe LUT may be used to dynamically parametrise some bound or linear constraints. An analogous approach is given in Song and Lau (2022) where a workspace in actuator space is \u201cconvexified\u201d and passed to an MPC. \n\nIn any case, an approximate process for creating a mapping is given below. Let **X**<sup>_\u2217_</sup> **a**<sup>be the set of all sam-</sup> pled points in the actuator space (which should be as small as possible) for a given simulator and let **Y**<sup>_\u2217_</sup> be the same for driver states. All non-sampled states are mapped using interpolation or extrapolation. \n\n#### **Algorithm 1:** Populate workspace mapping LUT \n\n\n\n<!-- Start of picture text -->\n1 for  s \u2208 simulators  do<br>2 for Xa \u2208 X \u2217 a ,  Y  \u2208 Y \u2217 do<br>3 LUT [ s ][\u201c x \u201d] .append ( XYa )<br>\ufffd \ufffd<br>4 if  kinematics model available  then<br>5 Determine  Ylim using kinematics<br>model<br>6 else<br>7 Experimentally determine  Ylim by<br>perturbing simulator about  Xa<br>8 LUT [ s ][\u201c y \u201d] .append ( Ylim )<br>9 end<br>10 end<br><!-- End of picture text -->\n\n**Stuttgart, 24-26 Sep 2025** \n\n**-2-** \n\n**DSC 2025 Europe**<sup>VR</sup> \n\n**Craig Brown** **_et al._** \n\n## ",
        "gemini_summary": "This text proposes a **decoupled architecture** for motion simulator workspace limiting, aiming to solve the complexity and simulator-dependency issues mentioned in the introduction.\n\n### Key Concepts\n\n*   **Decoupled Design:** The authors advocate for moving the \"Workspace Limiter\" out of the kinematics chain and making it an independent, modular subsystem (as illustrated in Figure 1). By performing limiting on **inertial (world) coordinate states** rather than actuator states, the system becomes hardware-agnostic.\n*   **Unified Workflow:** Because the limiter acts on the driver\u2019s motion (position, velocity, acceleration) in world space, the same algorithm can be applied to any simulator regardless of its physical configuration. Only the mapping between the simulator's specific kinematics and the universal workspace limits needs to be adjusted.\n*   **Mapping the Workspace:** Since calculating an analytical workspace is often mathematically impossible or overly complex for redundant-DOF systems, the authors propose using **Look-up Tables (LUTs)** or **Piecewise Affine Functions (PWAs)**.\n    *   These tables store the feasible bounds for the driver\u2019s state based on the current simulator configuration.\n    *   Limits can be defined either through mathematical modeling (if available) or empirical measurement (perturbing the simulator to find boundaries).\n*   **Flexibility and Implementation:** The method allows practitioners to choose their level of precision: they can use a highly detailed model or a simplified, interpolated approximation based on catalogue values. This approach maintains the performance of the Motion Cueing Algorithm (MCA) while ensuring the simulator stays within safe operational boundaries, regardless of the physical design.\n\n### Summary of the Workflow\n1.  **Populate:** Create a Look-up Table (LUT) for a specific simulator by mapping actuator states to allowable world-space limits.\n2.  **Separate:** Insert the Workspace Limiter as a standalone component that intercepts the \"desired driver states\" from the Motion Cueing Algorithm.\n3.  **Constraint:** The limiter uses the LUT to adjust the desired motion to \"feasible states,\" which are then passed to the kinematics transform to move the platform. \n\nThis methodology offers a practical, scalable, and standardized solution for large simulator facilities managing diverse hardware."
    },
